 with\nsimple functional forms.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 19 Nov 2017 21:11:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-28"}
{"id":"1711.07081","submitter":"Matthew Fickus","authors":"Matthew Fickus, John Jasper, Emily J. King, Dustin G. Mixon","title":"Equiangular tight frames that contain regular simplices","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.FA math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An equiangular tight frame (ETF) is a type of optimal packing of lines in\nEuclidean space. A regular simplex is a special type of ETF in which the number\nof vectors is one more than the dimension of the space they span. In this\npaper, we consider ETFs that contain a regular simplex, that is, have the\nproperty that a subset of its vectors forms a regular simplex. As we explain,\nsuch ETFs are characterized as those that achieve equality in a certain\nwell-known bound from the theory of compressed sensing. We then consider the\nso-called binder of such an ETF, namely the set of all regular simplices that\nit contains. We provide a new algorithm for computing this binder in terms of\nproducts of entries of the ETF's Gram matrix. In certain circumstances, we show\nthis binder can be used to produce a particularly elegant Naimark complement of\nthe corresponding ETF. Other times, an ETF is a disjoint union of regular\nsimplices, and we show this leads to a certain type of optimal packing of\nsubspaces known as an equichordal tight fusion frame. We conclude by\nconsidering the extent to which these ideas can be applied to numerous known\nconstructions of ETFs, including harmonic ETFs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 19 Nov 2017 21:12:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-11-21"}
